The photos were published here on March 6, 2021 in a Facebook post shared more than 10,000 times.
“Uncovering the corpse of Ma Kyal Sin. 5-3-2021 (night),” the Burmese-language caption reads.
Kyal Sin, nicknamed “Angel”,  was one of 38 anti-coup protesters killed in a brutal crackdown in Myanmar on March 3, 2021.
Her death attracted worldwide attention after images emerged of the 19-year-old at the protest wearing a t-shirt that read “Everything will be ok”.
Kyal Sin’s grave was exhumed by authorities for examination shortly after her death.
State media MRTV said the body was exhumed with the permission of the family, claiming a subsequent investigation into material found on the body proved that she was not killed by the police.
Videos of local residents discovering the grave had been exhumed have been circulating on social media.
The misleading photos were also shared alongside a similar claim here, here and here on Facebook, and here and here on Twitter.
However, the photos have been taken out of context and were posted online before Kyal Sin's death.
A keyword search led to this TikTok video published on December 10, 2020, which shows soldiers digging up an old bomb.
The caption of the TikTok video reads: “A bomb found in Kyaukpadaung”.
Kyaukpadaung is a town in Mandalay Region of Central Myanmar.
